revision.text:
{{Infobox person | name = Carlos Astrada | image = Carlos astrada.jpg | caption = | image_size = 200px | birth_date = February 26, 1894 | birth_place = [[Córdoba, Argentina]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1970|12|23|1894|2|26}} | death_place = [[Buenos Aires]] | nationality = Argentine | alma_mater = [[National University of Córdoba]] | occupation = Academic | networth = | religion = | spouse = | children = | residence = | salary = }} '''Carlos Astrada''' (February 26, 1894 – December 23, 1970) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] philosopher.
Astrada was born in [[Córdoba, Argentina|Córdoba]]. He completed his secondary school studies at the [[Colegio Nacional de Monserrat]] in Córdoba, and his university studies in law at the [[National University of Córdoba]]. His 1926 essay "The Epistemological Problem in Philosophy", earned an Astrada scholarship to [[Germany]]. He studied at the Universities of [[Cologne]], [[Bonn]], and [[Freiburg]], under [[Max Scheler]], [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Martin Heidegger]] and [[Oskar Becker]] during his four years there.
When he returned to Argentina from [[Germany]], Astrada was designated the head of Publications and Conferences in the Social Institute of the [[University of Litoral]] (1933-1934). There he began a vast career in distinct academic functions of the country: he was an adjunct professor of The History of Modern and Contemporary [[Philosophy]] in the School of Philosophy and Letter in the [[University of Buenos Aires]] (1936-1947); Professor of Ethics in the School of Science and Humanities in Education at the [[University of La Plata]] in [[La Plata]] (1937-1947); Professor of Philosophy in the [[Colegio Nacional de Buenos Aires]] (1939-1949); Professor of Nomology and Metaphysics in the School of Philosophy and Letters in the [[University of Buenos Aires]] (1947-1956); Director of the Institute of Philosophy in the University of Buenos Aires (1948-1956), and other posts. Astrada died in [[Buenos Aires]] in 1970.
