'''Emanuel Vogel Gerhart''' (born [[Freeburg, Pennsylvania|Freeburg]], [[Snyder County, Pennsylvania]], 13 June 1817; died [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]], 6 May 1904) was an [[United States|American]] minister of the [[German Reformed Church]].
==Biography== He was educated at Marshall College (now [[Franklin & Marshall College]]) and at the [[Mercersburg Theological Seminary]]. After acting as president of [[Heidelberg College]] in 1851 he became [[professor]] of [[theology]] in the Theological Seminary of [[Tiffin, Ohio|Tiffin]], [[Ohio]], whence he was called to the presidency of [[Franklin and Marshall College]] in 1855, where he also lectured on mental and moral [[philosophy]]. In 1868, he was appointed [[professor]] at the Reformed Church Seminary, [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]]. He edited [[Frederick Augustus Rauch]]'s ''Inner life'' and, for several years, the ''Mercersburg Review'', and wrote ''Philosophy and Logic'' (1858) and ''Institutions of the Christian Religion'' (1891).
